step.tex:
y = 5\cos x + 3\sin x\rightarrow \left(eq 1\right)\\ \text{First calculating the first order derivative}\\ \begin{align} \dfrac{dy}{dx} &= \dfrac{d\left(5 \cos x + 3\sin x \right)}{dx}\\ &= - 5\sin x + 3\cos x \\ \end{align}\\ \text{Now calculating the second order derivative}\\ \begin{align}
\dfrac{d^2 y}{dx^2}&= \dfrac{d\left(- 5\sin x + 3\cos x\right)}{dx}\\ &= -5\cos x - 3\sin x\\
\end{align}\\ \text{By comparing \left(eq 1\right) and \dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2}}\text{we get}\\
\begin{align}
\dfrac{d^2 y}{dx^2}&= -5\cos x - 3\sin x\\ & = -(5\cos x + 3\sin x)\\ &= - y\\ \end{align}\\ \therefore \dfrac{d^2 y}{dx^2} - y = 0

step.reason:
\text{We have used the fact that }\dfrac{d(\sin \theta)}{d\theta} = \cos \theta\,\\
\text{and }\dfrac{d(\cos \theta)}{d\theta}= -\sin \theta\text{.Check your calculation}\\
\text{if you got something else.}
